chunks.translated_text:
The highest benevolence serves its master through love and cannot remain without action. Yet when it acts, it arises from the heart’s spontaneous impulse—truly, it does not act through deliberate effort. The highest righteousness serves its master through appropriateness and cannot remain without action. When it acts because it deems something appropriate, this is action with a purpose.

The highest propriety adorns emotions with ritual forms. When emotions accumulate within, propriety is used to express them. Yet the elaborate details of ritual are not what the multitude can necessarily follow. When one performs ritual and none respond, one may raise an arm and force compliance—this is not merely action but compulsion. Thus, when the Dao is lost, virtue follows; when virtue is lost, benevolence follows; when benevolence is lost, righteousness follows; when righteousness is lost, propriety follows. All descend from the Dao through five stages before reaching propriety.

Propriety is formality. When formality prevails, emotion declines. Propriety is deference. When deference meets no response, strife arises. Is propriety not the thinning of loyalty and trust, the harbinger of chaos? Those who claim foresight shine with external brilliance, boasting outwardly while neglecting what lies within. Excessive scrutiny exhausts the mind; excessive cleverness breeds confusion. Is foresight not the flower of the Dao and the beginning of folly? Thinness gives rise to chaos; superficiality leads to foolishness. Therefore, the great person dwells in thickness, not thinness; abides in substance, not superficiality—thus rejecting external wisdom and propriety in favor of the Dao and virtue.

Of old, those who attained the One:
Heaven attained the One and became clear;
Earth attained the One and became tranquil;
Spirits attained the One and became numinous;
Valleys attained the One and became full;
The myriad things attained the One and came to life;
Lords and kings attained the One and became the standard for the world.
Their attainment was one and the same.

If heaven had nothing to make it clear, it would fear splitting;
If earth had nothing to make it tranquil, it would fear erupting;
If spirits had nothing to make them numinous, they would fear fading;
If valleys had nothing to make them full, they would fear drying;
If the myriad things had nothing to make them live, they would fear perishing;
If lords and kings had nothing to make them the standard and esteemed their high position, they would fear toppling.
Thus, the noble takes the humble as its root; the high takes the low as its foundation. Therefore, lords and kings call themselves "the orphaned," "the widowed," and "the unworthy." Is this not taking the humble as their root? Is it not so?

Thus, accumulating many humble parts makes something noble, just as assembling wheels, shafts, axles, and a canopy makes a carriage. Without the humble, there is no nobility. If one seeks to accumulate many carriages, there will be no carriages. Lords and kings must forget their nobility, forget their loftiness, only then can they become the standard for the world. Do not desire to be lustrous like jade or coarse like stone—excessive distinction is unnecessary.

Of old, those who attained the One:
Heaven attained the One and became clear;
Earth attained the One and became tranquil;
Spirits attained the One and became numinous;
Valleys attained the One and became full;
The myriad things attained the One and came to life;
Lords and kings attained the One and became the standard for the world.
Though heaven and earth, things and people differ, their need to attain this One is the same.

If heaven had nothing to make it clear, it would fear splitting;
If earth had nothing to make it tranquil, it would fear erupting;
If spirits had nothing to make them numinous, they would fear fading;
If valleys had nothing to make them full, they would fear drying;
If the myriad things had nothing to make them live, they would fear perishing;
If lords and kings had nothing to make them the standard and merely occupied positions of high nobility, they would fear toppling—how grave this is! The One cannot but be attained.

How do lords and kings attain the One? It is simply by not esteeming themselves, not exalting themselves. The noble takes the humble as its root; the high takes the low as its foundation. How can one esteem or exalt oneself? Therefore, lords and kings call themselves "the orphaned," "the widowed," and "the unworthy," using humble terms to name themselves. Is this not refusing to esteem themselves and taking the humble as their root? Is it not so?

The power of the world arises from uniting many humble parts to form nobility, just as a carriage is formed by assembling wheels, shafts, axles, and a canopy. Without the humble, there is no nobility. If one seeks to accumulate many carriages, there will be no carriages. Lords and kings must forget their nobility, forget their loftiness, only then can they become the standard for the world. Do not desire to be lustrous like jade or coarse like stone—excessive distinction is unnecessary.

Reversion is the movement of the Dao; weakness is the function of the Dao. The things of the world are born from being; being is born from non-being. When people do not outwardly chase but inwardly return, they enter the beginning of the Dao. Reversion is the movement of the Dao. Those who possess the Dao do not compete with things but naturally abide in weakness. Weakness is the function of the Dao. Why is this so? Because all things in the world are born from being, and being is born from non-being. Non-being is the natural state of the Dao. Reversion means abandoning being and tending toward non-being. Moving from being toward non-being is called the movement of the Dao. When one becomes one with the Dao, even stillness cannot be named—how much less movement? Weakness means being without departing from non-being. Not departing from non-being is called the function of the Dao. If one investigates its essence, it is also nothingness alone.

The highest scholar, hearing the Dao, diligently practices it.
The middling scholar, hearing the Dao, wavers between belief and doubt.
The lowest scholar, hearing the Dao, laughs loudly at it.
If it is not laughed at, it would not be the Dao.
Therefore, the established sayings state:
The bright Dao seems dim;
The advancing Dao seems to retreat;
The level Dao seems uneven;
The highest virtue seems like a valley;
Great whiteness seems sullied;
Abundant virtue seems insufficient;
Established virtue seems lax;
True substance seems to change;
Great squares have no corners;
Great vessels are late in completion;
Great music has a faint sound;
Great images have no form.
The Dao is hidden and nameless.
Yet only the Dao is good at bestowing and completing.

The highest scholar, hearing the Dao, diligently practices it.
The middling scholar, hearing the Dao, wavers between belief and doubt and cannot necessarily practice it.
The lowest scholar, hearing the Dao, laughs loudly at it.
If it is not laughed at by the lowest scholar, it would not be the Dao. Why is this so? The ancients who established sayings said:
Those who clarify the Dao do so by clarifying themselves alone, not competing with the world—thus, the bright Dao seems dim.
Those who advance the Dao do so by advancing themselves alone, not competing with the world—thus, the advancing Dao seems to retreat.
Those who level the Dao are at peace with all things in the world. Though not what others can attain, they appear similar to others.
The highest virtue does not claim possession of virtue—thus, it is lowly like a valley.
Great whiteness does not depart from defilement to be white—thus, it seems sullied by the dust.
Abundant virtue does not consider itself abundant—thus, it always seems insufficient.
Established virtue is diligent in cultivating its nature and simple in its interactions with things—thus, it appears careless and lax.
True substance follows nature and wanders without attachment—thus, it appears inconstant and changing.
Great squares are inwardly upright and conduct themselves without ostentation—thus, they show no corners.
Great vessels are late in completion—their completion cannot be hastened.
Great music has a faint sound—its sound cannot be heard.
Great images have no form—their form cannot be contained.
This is beyond the calculations of middling and lowly people—how could they not ridicule it?

The essence of the Dao is hidden and difficult to see, without anything to name it. When it manifests in things, only the Dao is good at bestowing and completing all things. Though all things receive its gifts, they do not know it—it is fitting that the lowest scholars laugh at it.

The Dao gives birth to the One;
The One gives birth to the Two;
The Two give birth to the Three;
The Three give birth to the myriad things.
The myriad things bear yin and embrace yang;
The qi of the void harmonizes them.

What people dislike are "the orphaned," "the widowed," and "the unworthy," yet kings and lords use these as their titles. Thus, things may be diminished yet benefit, or benefited yet diminish. What people teach, I also teach: "The strong and overbearing do not meet their natural end." I will take this as the father of my teaching.

